00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:36.480
They start to like knock the cobwebs off some of the fundamental programming stuff they had for maybe 20, 30 years ago when they went to school.

00:10:36.760 --> 00:10:39.420
And then start to add these new elements that are there.

00:10:39.420 --> 00:10:42.340
XML didn't exist for some of these guys when they went through it.

00:10:42.340 --> 00:10:43.900
And YAML certainly didn't.

00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:44.600
And so showing them the value.

00:10:44.600 --> 00:10:51.620
And so showing them the value, showing them how to use it, how to connect to a device through Python using one of these APIs that are available.

00:10:51.620 --> 00:10:55.180
And why is that better than doing it the way that they're doing it today?

00:10:55.180 --> 00:11:01.300
Because that's a big part of the discussion often is showing them that there is value in making this journey.

00:11:01.300 --> 00:11:04.980
Right. Because a lot of them probably didn't decide to be programmers.

00:11:04.980 --> 00:11:10.080
I mean, maybe that's a good way to segue into like what is the background of a typical network engineer?

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:17.720
Like you said, maybe they have some programming experience, some technical experience, but they probably didn't choose networking because they wanted to be a programmer.

00:11:17.720 --> 00:11:19.280
So what's the story there?

00:11:19.280 --> 00:11:20.200
What do you experience?

00:11:20.420 --> 00:11:24.020
Yeah, they absolutely didn't choose networking because they wanted to be a programmer.

00:11:24.020 --> 00:11:36.240
In fact, one of the things I hear an awful lot when we start to have these discussions is in some cases they're coming kicking and screaming because they really don't want to be a programmer and they don't want to learn these new skills.

00:11:36.240 --> 00:11:48.460
And it's helping them recognize that just because you're going to do some automation, you're going to learn some Python, doesn't mean that you're now a software developer because these skills are becoming relevant to data scientists, to engineers, to everybody.

00:11:48.700 --> 00:11:51.160
And so there's this blurring and the gap.

00:11:51.160 --> 00:11:58.320
A typical network engineer has a foundation in kind of network theory and connectivity areas that are there.

00:11:58.320 --> 00:12:03.780
So there's the typical kind of OSA model of layer one, two, three, all the way up to seven.

00:12:03.780 --> 00:12:07.040
So they understand the fundamentals of how network traffic works.

00:12:07.040 --> 00:12:15.500
They spend their days dealing with networking concepts like IP space and ports and firewalls and load balancers.

00:12:15.660 --> 00:12:22.800
So all of these elements, these foundational elements that help make applications function that the cloud relies on to go through.

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:28.840
The network engineer is coming in these discussions with this understanding of how kind of this foundation goes through.

00:12:28.840 --> 00:12:37.400
And despite the fact that in many cases they don't think that they've done a lot of automation or they've done a lot of programming or scripting in their previous life, let's say,

00:12:37.600 --> 00:12:45.500
many of them have because every network engineer I've ever known has been a problem solver and is always looking for ways to do things a little bit better.

00:12:45.500 --> 00:12:51.180
And so for the longest time, and in some cases still today, it's a CLI interface.

00:12:51.180 --> 00:12:53.540
A command line interface is how we configure a network.

00:12:53.740 --> 00:12:59.340
Maybe a bash script or something like that that'll like process, you know, like automate that in that sense, right?

00:12:59.340 --> 00:12:59.860
Exactly.

00:12:59.860 --> 00:13:01.820
There's there's expect scripting, right?

00:13:01.820 --> 00:13:07.240
So send this and expect to get this back and then send this other one away because there's network.

00:13:07.240 --> 00:13:11.120
Every network engineer I've known really hates having to repeat themselves over and over again.

00:13:11.300 --> 00:13:14.740
And so they've figured out ways to make their jobs better.

00:13:14.740 --> 00:13:26.200
And so that's the big thing I'm trying to show them is this move into using Python is actually going to make what they've done in the past simpler and actually a little bit more pleasurable because we can take away some of the challenges that were there.

00:13:26.200 --> 00:13:29.880
There is a bit of that, I don't want to say hurdle, but like a plateau to get people over.

00:13:29.880 --> 00:13:35.800
And that first aha moment, that's one of my favorite things to see when I'm working with somebody is when they get it.

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:37.100
They understand the value.

00:13:37.100 --> 00:13:39.240
They understand that it's not this thing to be dreaded.

00:13:39.240 --> 00:13:39.480
Right.

