So you talked about getting into Python almost because of the cloud and things like that.

00:13:54.680 --> 00:14:05.500
It seems to me the cloud movement itself has probably dramatically changed what it means to be a network engineer in the first place, right?

00:14:05.500 --> 00:14:07.420
Like there used to be these physical things.

00:14:07.420 --> 00:14:09.500
You could log into them and mess with them.

00:14:09.580 --> 00:14:14.820
And now it's APIs and VMs and data centers far away from you.

00:14:14.820 --> 00:14:15.060
Yeah.

00:14:15.060 --> 00:14:16.480
It's completely accurate.

00:14:16.480 --> 00:14:23.760
I mean, it comes back on network engineers ourselves to some extent that it seemed that we got so far away from what a network really was.

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:32.380
And we started to see a network as these physical routers and switches and firewalls that we touched rather than the act of connecting together the pieces that are there.

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:34.140
And so I talk a lot.

00:14:34.140 --> 00:14:38.420
One of the conversations I give is this evolution to networking in the programmable age.

00:14:38.420 --> 00:14:43.040
And I go back in time to when the network really was just routers and switches and servers.

00:14:43.040 --> 00:14:44.100
Yeah.

00:14:44.100 --> 00:14:46.220
You refer to that as the four ages of networking.

00:14:46.220 --> 00:14:47.300
Do you want to take us through it?

00:14:47.400 --> 00:14:48.280
Yeah, exactly.

00:14:48.280 --> 00:14:56.100
And so originally, right, in what I often call kind of like the stone age of networking, things were simple.

00:14:56.100 --> 00:15:02.500
We had servers and workstations and printers, and they connected into switches, and then maybe we had a router to communicate with them.

00:15:02.720 --> 00:15:13.340
And the biggest thing network engineers were focused on is kind of like making sure that spanning tree didn't cause issues in the network and that if they were going to have to use some VLANs to carve computers and printers off.

00:15:13.340 --> 00:15:18.520
Because at that point, the network was you could walk into any closet and you could reach out and touch it.

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:23.340
It was usually like teal green and had Cisco written on it, and that was the network.

00:15:23.340 --> 00:15:25.660
And there were cables, and it was really easy.

00:15:26.300 --> 00:15:36.600
But over time, the first hint of the kind of the changes to networking that I started to see, and many of us did, was virtualization, x86 virtualization with VMware and these other things.

00:15:36.600 --> 00:15:39.580
And the concept of a V switch came out.

00:15:39.580 --> 00:15:50.580
And it wasn't even that long ago, I would have heated discussions with networking and server teams about whose responsibility it was for the network inside of a hypervisor.

00:15:50.920 --> 00:15:58.580
Because the network guys didn't want to do it because it wasn't a physical switch, and the server guys had no idea what a VLAN was or what a tag was.

00:15:58.580 --> 00:16:01.520
And so there was this huge challenge that went through.

00:16:01.520 --> 00:16:10.480
And sadly, in many of those cases, the networking guys just stuck their head in the sand and said, you know what, I'm just going to let the server guys deal with it because it doesn't really matter.

00:16:11.040 --> 00:16:20.460
And then as we moved from kind of that stone age, that early piece that went in into the dot-com era and all of these other pieces, new things went after us.

00:16:20.460 --> 00:16:24.300
After x86 virtualization, we got blade switches.

00:16:24.300 --> 00:16:26.560
And so we had these new physical pieces.

00:16:26.560 --> 00:16:33.680
But rather than buying a blade switch from a networking vendor, maybe it's being bought from a server company.

00:16:33.680 --> 00:16:37.420
And so networking guys were once again saying, you know what, that's not my stuff.

00:16:37.420 --> 00:16:38.520
I'm not going to deal with it.

00:16:38.820 --> 00:16:42.940
And then what was it, two years ago, we started to see kind of the container explosion.

00:16:42.940 --> 00:16:51.920
And so now we've got networking inside of Linux servers that are behind virtual switches that are running embedded inside of a blade server someplace.

00:16:51.920 --> 00:16:59.000
And the networking guys are finally realizing that there is a lot of networking that is happening outside of their physical switches.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:01.920
And that's been a big kind of aha moment.

00:17:01.920 --> 00:17:04.200
And then we can bring in the cloud elements.

00:17:04.200 --> 00:17:11.500
Because when we talk about the cloud, if we're talking public cloud, in these cases, now we're sending workloads and resources up there.

00:17:11.500 --> 00:17:17.260
And we don't even have the luxury as a network engineer to know that at some point that traffic will go through my physical switch.

00:17:17.260 --> 00:17:18.640
Because you don't own those physical switches.

00:17:18.640 --> 00:17:25.600
Yeah, the one final bastion of thing they claimed is theirs has now been virtualized and moved out.

00:17:25.600 --> 00:17:27.760
And so now it's all the other stuff.

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:29.140
They're like, well, that's not really my problem.

00:17:29.140 --> 00:17:31.980
Like, that's like what's left that they now need to work with, right?

00:17:32.240 --> 00:17:33.200
Exactly, exactly.

00:17:33.200 --> 00:17:50.900
And so as the evolution from virtualization to containers to cloud, and I love the fact that cloud is now starting to turn into this, rather than people thinking of the cloud as a place, like AWS is the cloud or Google or Azure or one of these other cloud providers.

00:17:51.180 --> 00:17:56.380
This idea of cloud is just kind of an approach, a fully programmable approach to infrastructure.

00:17:56.380 --> 00:18:01.800
And so I've got customers today that consider their data centers their cloud on that side as well.

00:18:01.800 --> 00:18:06.340
And they want to manage their clouds the same way that they consume and manage their other ones.

00:18:06.340 --> 00:18:08.340
This is with this huge pressure.

00:18:08.340 --> 00:18:09.280
Yeah, I think it is.

00:18:09.280 --> 00:18:19.140
And I think what's really interesting is, you know, there's this joke or, I don't know, sarcasm or whatever that says, you know, the cloud is really just somebody else's computer.

00:18:19.140 --> 00:18:19.440
Yeah.

00:18:19.960 --> 00:18:20.300
Right.

00:18:20.300 --> 00:18:22.820
Which I think that's a little bit disingenuous.

00:18:22.820 --> 00:18:23.640
Technically, it's true.

00:18:23.640 --> 00:18:24.560
Someone owns the computer.

00:18:24.560 --> 00:18:32.140
But I think fundamentally, the cloud is a programmable set of infrastructure that you don't have to go touch, right?

00:18:32.140 --> 00:18:34.760
And that programmability could be within your data center.

00:18:34.760 --> 00:18:35.620
It could be AWS.

00:18:35.620 --> 00:18:38.360
It could be somewhere else like Linode or something, right?

00:18:38.360 --> 00:18:46.900
It's the ability to write some code and servers and switches and networks come into existence, I think, in my mind, at least.

00:18:46.900 --> 00:18:48.220
Yeah, I think that's accurate.

00:18:48.220 --> 00:18:54.480
The idea that the cloud, you don't have to worry about the infrastructure is true if you're consuming cloud.

00:18:54.720 --> 00:18:59.260
But there's also this other group of engineers that are building clouds, right?

00:18:59.260 --> 00:18:59.760
Right.

00:18:59.760 --> 00:19:01.060
And somebody has to do that.

00:19:01.060 --> 00:19:12.240
And it's been interesting to watch the pendulum swing from 100% public cloud strategies to 100% hybrid cloud and then some people coming back to fully private cloud.

00:19:12.240 --> 00:19:23.580
If any part of an organization and enterprise strategy involves some element of private cloud, be that for data sovereignty or security or cost, because that does come up occasionally.

00:19:23.580 --> 00:19:32.400
Well, now the people that are writing and deploying apps want to consume the cloud inside of your data center the same way they did it in the public cloud.

00:19:32.580 --> 00:19:38.120
But now you have to have a team that can build the infrastructure that can offer that service.

00:19:38.120 --> 00:19:39.980
And that, I think, is the huge pressure.

00:19:39.980 --> 00:19:45.260
And that maybe means programming API, like creating APIs for them to consume and stuff like that, right?

00:19:45.580 --> 00:19:45.940
Exactly.

00:19:45.940 --> 00:19:53.760
It hasn't come up a lot, but I've had two cases specifically with enterprises where they had taken on, they had done some automation of their own.

00:19:53.760 --> 00:19:55.640
They were doing a lot of work in the networking space.

00:19:55.640 --> 00:20:06.040
But they were starting to get requests from application teams and systems and services teams to offer the network services through an API interface.

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:17.140
And so they were starting to build an API that their application teams could consume and their operations teams could consume to make general connectivity or logging requests or information.

00:20:17.140 --> 00:20:23.240
And so we got to actually, it was a really fun project we did because we got to show, okay, well, let's talk about API design.

00:20:23.240 --> 00:20:24.940
How do you build an API?

00:20:24.940 --> 00:20:34.260
What makes an API good so that your developers who are used to consuming APIs from Google and Azure and all these other folks will be happy about consuming your API?

00:20:34.260 --> 00:20:48.520
All of a sudden you're put into the place where like you have to compete on API design with Google and Amazon, which, you know, just a while ago, maybe you were even really interested in writing APIs and you're kind of in the deep end at that point, right?

00:20:48.520 --> 00:20:49.120
Exactly.

00:20:49.120 --> 00:20:51.440
And those are the interesting pieces that are coming at it.

00:20:51.440 --> 00:20:56.840
And organizations are getting these changes and these adjustments so fast these days.

00:20:56.840 --> 00:21:02.020
And I think that's a big challenge that every industry has, but certainly the network engineers have.

00:21:02.120 --> 00:21:04.340
It's trying to figure out how do they keep up?

00:21:04.340 --> 00:21:09.340
How do they, it's, there's always that analogy of you're laying the track as the train is kind of approaching.

00:21:09.340 --> 00:21:12.740
And I think that that's never going to change in the IT space.

00:21:12.740 --> 00:21:21.500
And that's been a big struggle because for better or worse, the networking industry didn't have a lot of adjustments for several years, let's say decades in some cases.

00:21:21.740 --> 00:21:26.480
And this adjustment to cloud and programmability and automation is this massive pivot.

00:21:26.480 --> 00:21:31.940
And so now we've got a lot of engineers and network engineers out there just trying to figure out how do I keep up, right?

00:21:31.940 --> 00:21:32.760
What do I learn next?

00:21:32.760 --> 00:21:34.060
Where do I go through on this area?

00:21:34.060 --> 00:21:36.280
And that, that sense of overwhelming nature.

