What else is changing for them?

00:24:45.420 --> 00:24:49.180
What else is Python sort of changing that I don't even know to ask about?

00:24:49.180 --> 00:24:51.720
Yeah, I mean, I think that's the interesting one that goes through.

00:24:51.720 --> 00:24:58.640
One of the impacts of using Python to automate your network is kind of all of the things that come along with that.

00:24:58.640 --> 00:25:01.200
Because now they are writing some code someplace.

00:25:01.200 --> 00:25:05.480
And so there's all these new strategies around kind of where do we put code?

00:25:05.480 --> 00:25:09.320
And so at the same time we're teaching Python, we're teaching source control strategies.

00:25:09.580 --> 00:25:09.940
Of course.

00:25:09.940 --> 00:25:20.100
We're showing folks how to deal with branches and how to use issue logs and pull requests to go through, which then gets to take us down kind of a pipeline path and go in.

00:25:20.640 --> 00:25:33.140
One of the interesting pieces that often comes quickly is how fast an engineer goes from thinking Python is going to be their answer and then reaching out to some other management tool like Ansible, which is written in Python.

00:25:33.140 --> 00:25:35.100
But they say, you know, I don't have to learn Python.

00:25:35.100 --> 00:25:39.080
I can just go learn Ansible and fix all these issues and I'll just go down that path.

00:25:39.200 --> 00:25:49.600
And that goes for a little while and then all of the challenges that potentially come out of that come through and then eventually they're back to, okay, maybe I do really need to understand the Python under the hood.

00:25:49.600 --> 00:25:53.320
I can't just kind of absorb some new open source tool to make everything better.

00:25:53.320 --> 00:25:54.240
Yeah, for sure.

00:25:54.240 --> 00:25:58.000
Of course, that whole software carpentry side of things has got to come in, right?

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:07.000
Like as soon as you start to depend upon Python scripts to do your job, it's like, well, we should actually version control this and how do we share this together and how do we test it?

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:10.820
And just, you know, all those layers just start to come crashing in.

00:26:10.820 --> 00:26:11.820
It's pretty interesting.

00:26:11.820 --> 00:26:14.240
I had a question came in to me over LinkedIn.

00:26:14.240 --> 00:26:18.400
It was two days ago and it was from a network engineer who I've been talking with for a while.

00:26:18.400 --> 00:26:26.160
And he's like, all right, here's the challenge we have is I've got people across my organization writing automation scripts to do really interesting things.

00:26:26.360 --> 00:26:34.460
And we've made a lot of progress, but now we've got islands of automation and everybody's automation looks different and nobody can use everybody else's automation.

00:26:34.460 --> 00:26:37.640
So how do we, how do we bring these things together?

00:26:37.640 --> 00:26:41.740
And so we started to talk about things like coding style guides, right?

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:47.800
You have to come up with some, some approach and styles, not syntax, which means there's no right or wrong way.

00:26:47.800 --> 00:26:49.280
It's, it's kind of a consensus.

00:26:49.280 --> 00:26:52.300
Somebody has to say, this is how we do things.

00:26:52.420 --> 00:27:02.300
And then kind of making sure that people aren't porting their code and their scripts kind of on their machine and start to collaborate through repositories and go down that path.

00:27:02.300 --> 00:27:04.960
And, and that's an interesting piece that goes in.

00:27:04.960 --> 00:27:13.680
Moving network engineers away from the days where they, they would store their information in text files that were their version control was .v1, .v2, .v3.

00:27:13.680 --> 00:27:15.980
You really got to save it and zip it up.

00:27:16.120 --> 00:27:16.360
Yeah.

00:27:16.360 --> 00:27:16.900
Yeah.

00:27:16.900 --> 00:27:17.000
Yeah.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:25.220
And then teaching them just the magic that's offered and available inside using some sort of source control and version control system goes through.

00:27:25.220 --> 00:27:36.900
We spend probably just as much time trying to teach fundamentals of source control as fundamentals of Python and some of these early workshops, because that's what it takes to be successful in these areas.

00:27:36.900 --> 00:27:50.840
And having, having, having approached this myself and kind of stumbled my way through it, there's, there's things that I wish I would have started doing sooner that I'm trying to help network engineers today kind of learn from the mistakes that I made rather than having to go make the mistakes themselves.

00:27:50.840 --> 00:27:51.220
Yeah.

00:27:51.220 --> 00:27:54.240
Coming through this path, it sounds like many of them do.

00:27:54.240 --> 00:28:04.760
I'm sure they go through the experience of creating what you would think of as a script that does a very specific thing that you can run to.

00:28:04.760 --> 00:28:08.840
Well, there's actually this algorithm in here and these are the inputs of the algorithm.

00:28:08.840 --> 00:28:13.940
How do I turn this actually into say a library or a project someone else could consume?

00:28:13.940 --> 00:28:16.300
And how do we start to build these building blocks?

00:28:16.300 --> 00:28:19.260
I think that's probably an interesting transition as well.

00:28:19.260 --> 00:28:19.600
Yeah.

00:28:19.600 --> 00:28:20.540
It's interesting to go through.

00:28:20.540 --> 00:28:33.880
I mean, one of the, one of the strategies we use to try to break down the learning of automation and the value, the value prop that's there is, is we sit down and we say, okay, well, what are, what are like the five things that you spend almost every day doing?

00:28:33.880 --> 00:28:35.640
Or maybe we take a trouble ticket.

00:28:35.640 --> 00:28:37.580
What every trouble ticket comes through.

00:28:37.580 --> 00:28:43.920
Every organization usually has like, these are the information you need to gather before you ever start working on a trouble ticket.

00:28:43.920 --> 00:28:46.300
Well, let's, let's figure out how we can automate that.

00:28:46.300 --> 00:28:49.380
And then we break those up into these little pockets.

00:28:49.380 --> 00:28:56.840
And so maybe we've got a team of a dozen engineers and three of them work on step one, three of them work on step two, the rest of them that go through.

00:28:57.220 --> 00:29:05.600
And then the goal is by, is to show them how they can then consume everybody else's work and say, okay, well, we can pull in this other person's piece of code.

00:29:05.860 --> 00:29:06.860
And so you don't have to do that.

00:29:06.860 --> 00:29:13.980
And so you don't have to redo that yourself as long as you're kind of abiding by these kind of ideas of how these libraries work or inputs and outputs that go through it.

00:29:13.980 --> 00:29:15.020
You don't care.

00:29:15.020 --> 00:29:17.480
Like, it doesn't matter what happened inside of their function.

00:29:17.480 --> 00:29:20.860
You just know what you need to send it and what to expect to come back.

00:29:20.920 --> 00:29:24.660
And if we all agree on that, well, you saved yourself two hours worth of work.

00:29:24.660 --> 00:29:25.180
Every day.

00:29:25.180 --> 00:29:25.620
Yeah.

00:29:25.620 --> 00:29:26.400
Or something like that, right?

00:29:26.400 --> 00:29:26.780
Absolutely.

00:29:26.780 --> 00:29:27.920
Yeah.

00:29:27.920 --> 00:29:28.720
That's pretty awesome.

00:29:29.040 --> 00:29:36.480
So maybe now's a good time to talk about some of the major packages that people might use for in this programmability space.

00:29:36.480 --> 00:29:45.160
So, of course, probably a lot of these devices have direct APIs and you could, you know, create a JSON request and like send a post or something over.

00:29:45.160 --> 00:29:48.240
But it's probably better to use some higher level library, right?

00:29:48.240 --> 00:29:48.680
Yeah.

00:29:48.680 --> 00:29:50.340
So there's a bunch of them that go through.

00:29:50.340 --> 00:29:52.240
And so we've mentioned Ansible already.

00:29:52.240 --> 00:29:53.440
Ansible is written in Python.

00:29:53.440 --> 00:29:57.120
Most people just use it as a program rather than as a library.

00:29:57.660 --> 00:30:03.140
But we do have some folks writing Ansible modules to extend out the capabilities that are there.

00:30:03.140 --> 00:30:03.420
Right.

00:30:03.420 --> 00:30:07.740
Most of the time, programming Ansible is like constructing YAML files, right?

00:30:07.740 --> 00:30:08.340
Exactly.

00:30:08.340 --> 00:30:13.700
And until the module you need isn't there or it's not working exactly right.

00:30:13.700 --> 00:30:14.760
And so those go through.

00:30:14.760 --> 00:30:22.040
But for folks building kind of the raw Python and they want to go down that path, I always start with the fundamental toolkits, right?

00:30:22.040 --> 00:30:23.240
You mentioned the APIs.

00:30:24.180 --> 00:30:28.160
And so the key networking APIs today are basic REST fundamentals.

00:30:28.160 --> 00:30:34.420
And so REST APIs, we're going to consume them the same way that anybody else is using requests library is going to go through.

00:30:34.420 --> 00:30:35.700
So that's an early one we teach.

00:30:35.700 --> 00:30:43.660
Inside of the networking space, the long-lauded and also kind of disparaged API of SNMP still exists.

00:30:44.320 --> 00:30:49.620
And so occasionally we work with PI SNMP to work through and bring SNMP details in.

00:30:49.620 --> 00:31:06.060
But frankly, the newest interfaces, and these are new standards that were developed by the IETF for network programmability specifically, are netconf and restconf, which are model-driven programmability interfaces based on data models that are agreed upon and well understood.

00:31:06.600 --> 00:31:10.020
And then these interfaces return data either in XML and JSON.

00:31:10.020 --> 00:31:13.240
So now we're getting into kind of true programmability interfaces.

00:31:13.240 --> 00:31:20.700
And so the NC client library is what we use to communicate with netconf at their, with the netconf protocol.

00:31:20.700 --> 00:31:34.900
And then after we get kind of, let's say, the hammers, the screwdrivers, the nuts and bolts, kind of understanding those pieces, then we can step up to some of the libraries that have been developed to kind of consume those and offer an easier way to go through.

00:31:35.160 --> 00:31:41.520
And so in the netconf model-driven programmability space, there's actually an open source project called YDK.

00:31:41.520 --> 00:31:54.540
It's Yang Development Kit that was spearheaded, and most of the development actually comes out of Cisco, which aims to wrap up the data models in a Pythonic library so that you don't have to make native API calls.

00:31:54.540 --> 00:31:57.220
You can just work with them through a Pythonic library.

00:31:57.220 --> 00:32:00.920
Then there's the configuration management tooling that's out there.

00:32:00.920 --> 00:32:08.820
And so the good folks over at Spotify started out the Napalm project, which is all about multi-vendor kind of network configuration pushes.

